  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  _isReadable: 1
  pageImage: {fileID: 21300000, guid: 0c937bc4d209ea8479e01cb36119d5a5, type: 3}
  pageScale: {x: 900, y: 900}
  hasMultPages: 1
  noteReverseText:
  - "The villagers speak in hushed tones about the old chapel on the cliff \u2014
    not because of superstition, but because they remember. Before the land split,
    before the sea swallowed the lower fields, that chapel was the heart of the valley.
    I was just a child then, chasing fireflies and scribbling symbols I didn\u2019t
    understand into the dirt.\n\nThen came the storm \u2014 unnatural and sudden.
    The sky didn\u2019t crack with lightning. It split open, like paper peeled back
    by invisible claws. From it fell no rain, but a hum... deep and constant. Every
    bell in the valley rang, all at once. Then silence. Just silence.\n\nThe next
    morning, the chapel doors were sealed with melted iron. And inside, they say,
    was Father Coyle \u2014 or what was left of him."
  - "It's been 26 years since that night, and now the earth\u2019s begun to quake
    again. I broke the seal on the chapel this morning. The hinges had fused to the
    stone \u2014 not rusted, not worn, just... fused. I thought I\u2019d find decay.
    Instead, I found it untouched. Clean. Preserved like time forgot to move inside
    those walls.\n\nThere was a book on the altar \u2014 not scripture, but a journal.
    Father Coyle\u2019s name was written on the first page. The second page held
    just one line: \u201CHe said we could save them, if only we watched.\u201D\n\nBeneath
    the altar, I found a lens. Not glass \u2014 crystal. Warm to the touch. I don\u2019t
    know what it shows yet, but when I looked through it, I swear I saw the chapel
    as it was before the storm. Full of people. All staring right at me."
  mainTextAreaScale: {x: 495, y: 795}
